<hw>moot</hw> <pr>(m⟦oomac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>A ring for gauging wooden pins.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Moot
<hw>Moot</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mooted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mooting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>moten</ets>,
<ets>motien</ets>, AS. <ets>m⟦omac⟧tan</ets> to meet or assemble for
conversation, to discuss, dispute, fr. <ets>m⟦omac⟧t</ets>,
<ets>gem⟦omac⟧t</ets>, a meeting, an assembly; akin to Icel.
<ets>m⟦omac⟧t</ets>, MHG. <ets>muoz</ets>. Cf. <er>Meet</er> to come
together.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To argue for and against; to debate;
to discuss; to propose for discussion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A problem which hardly has been mentioned, much less
<qex>mooted</qex>, in this country.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically: To discuss by way of exercise; to
argue for practice; to propound and discuss in a mock court.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>First a case is appointed to be <qex>mooted</qex> by certain young
men, containing some doubtful controversy.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Elyot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To render inconsequential, as having no effect on
the practical outcome; to render academic; <as>as, the ruling that the
law was invalid <ex>mooted</ex> the question of whether he actually
violated it</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Moot
<hw>Moot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To argue or plead in a
supposed case.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a difference between <qex>mooting</qex> and pleading;
between fencing and fighting.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Moot
<hw>Moot</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m⟦omac⟧t</ets>,
<ets>gem⟦omac⟧t</ets>, a meeting; -- usually in comp.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>mote</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
meeting for discussion and deliberation; esp., a meeting of the people
of a village or district, in Anglo-Saxon times, for the discussion and
settlement of matters of common interest; -- usually in composition;
<as>as, folk-<ex>moot</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>J. R.
Green.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[From <er>Moot</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>A
discussion or debate; especially, a discussion of fictitious causes by
way of practice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pleading used in courts and chancery called
<qex>moots</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Elyot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moot case</b></col>, <cd>a case or question to be mooted;
a disputable case; an unsettled question.</cd> <au>Dryden.</au> --
<col><b>Moot court</b></col>, <cd>a mock court, such as is held by
students of law for practicing the conduct of law cases.</cd> --
<col><b>Moot point</b></col>, <cd>a point or question to be debated; a
doubtful question.</cd> -- <col><b>to make moot</b></col> <pos>v.
t.</pos> <cd>to render moot{2}; to moot{3}.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Moot
<hw>Moot</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Subject, or open, to
argument or discussion; undecided; debatable; mooted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of purely theoretical or academic interest; having
no practical consequence; <as>as, the team won in spite of the bad call,
and whether the ruling was correct is a <ex>moot</ex>
question</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mootable</ent>⟦br⟧
